const ARTICLES=[
  {title:"The Two Shocks",summary:"There is a reassuring narrative in FE: AI is coming for the office jobs, so the future belongs to the trades. That narrative is not wrong. But it is incomplete. The second shock — embodied robotics — changes the question entirely.",category:"Education",read_time:"6 minutes",slug:"the-two-shocks",date:"2026-02-14",featured:true,body:`There is a reassuring narrative taking hold across Further Education: AI is coming for the office jobs, so the future belongs to the trades. Plumbing. Electrical. Construction. Retrofitting. Care. The physical, hands-on work that no chatbot can do. Expand workshop space, recruit more technical tutors, deepen employer links, and the college is future-proofed.

That narrative is not wrong. But it is incomplete.

What FE is living through now is the first of two shocks. The first is already visible: generative AI is reducing the cost of routine cognitive work and reshaping the value of office-based skills. The second is still emerging: advances in robotics and embodied AI will, over time, begin to change the value of some physical work too. The strategic challenge for colleges is not choosing between these shocks. It is responding to the first while preparing for the second.

The First Shock: When Thinking Becomes Cheap

The first shock is easier to see because it is already affecting labour-market expectations. The World Economic Forum's 2025 survey of large employers points to the sharpest declines in clerical and secretarial roles over the 2025–2030 period, while demand rises in skilled trades, care roles, and other occupations rooted in physical presence, human interaction, or complex real-world environments. In other words, the immediate response many colleges are making is rational: when routine desk work becomes easier to automate, practical and place-based capability becomes more valuable.

That pattern is visible in England's FE data too, though less neatly than some of the rhetoric suggests. Official Department for Education statistics for 2024/25 show business, administration and law enrolments down 8.1%, while construction, planning and the built environment rose 5.4%. Construction is also the only subject area to have increased year-on-year for the last five years, rising from 39,950 enrolments in 2019/20 to 62,570 in 2024/25. But the picture is not simply "all practical courses up": health, public services and care enrolments actually fell 8.9% in the same period, even though it remains one of the largest subject areas overall.

So the near-term conclusion is not that "the trades are safe" in some absolute sense. It is that, right now, complex physical work in messy environments is one of the strongest hedges against the first wave of AI-driven disruption. That is why construction capacity has become such a live policy issue. The UK government has committed major new funding to expand college training places and facilities in response to construction shortages, and sector bodies are openly saying some colleges have had to turn potential students away in high-demand areas.

The Second Shock: When the Physical World Gets Smarter

But this is where the second shock matters.

The reason physical trades feel protected today is that the real world is hard. Language, documents, spreadsheets, and repetitive digital workflows were easier for AI to absorb than movement in unstructured environments. Writing an acceptable report turned out to be easier for machines than climbing a ladder, adjusting grip on an awkward tool, or navigating a cramped site with incomplete information. That asymmetry has defined the current moment.

Yet it would be a mistake to assume that asymmetry is permanent. Robotics has been moving more slowly than generative AI, but it has not been standing still. Vision-language-action systems, improved robot reasoning, and better multimodal world models are now pushing machines beyond fixed industrial routines toward more adaptive behaviour. Google's 2025 robotics releases were an important signal of that direction of travel, and the wider research field is advancing quickly. At the same time, serious observers are warning against hype: Stanford HAI has stressed the need for a more grounded view of robotics, and the OECD's 2025 capability indicators place current robotic systems at a level where they still perform best in structured settings and are not yet reliably capable of the multi-step, collaborative, unstructured work that would define a true breakthrough in general physical autonomy.

That means the second shock should not be described as "robots are about to replace the trades." That is too crude, and too early. The more accurate claim is that FE should now plan for a world in which physical occupations are gradually reconfigured by machines, just as cognitive occupations are being reconfigured by software. The first stage is not replacement. It is redistribution: more automation of routine sub-tasks, more machine assistance, more workflow redesign, and a growing premium on the humans who can supervise, adapt, troubleshoot, assure safety, and handle exceptions. McKinsey's recent work makes exactly this point, arguing that work is increasingly being reorganised around partnerships between people, agents, and robots rather than simple one-for-one substitution.

What Survives Both Shocks

For FE leaders, that changes the question. The question is no longer, "Which courses are safe from AI?" It is, "Which capabilities remain valuable across both shocks?"

The first is cyber-physical orchestration: the ability to understand a real-world problem, break it into parts, decide what can be delegated to software or machines, deploy the right tools, and intervene when those tools fail. This is not just digital literacy, and it is not just trade skill. It is a hybrid capability that combines practical judgment, spatial reasoning, systems thinking, safety awareness, and technological fluency. That capability becomes more valuable, not less, as AI and robotics improve.

The second is unstructured problem-solving. Old buildings, unpredictable sites, emergency repairs, retrofit work, live operational environments, and human bodies do not behave like clean datasets. The more variable, chaotic, and context-heavy the environment, the more valuable human judgment remains. This is why the future is unlikely to be kind to the most routine forms of manual work, but may still strongly reward technicians and practitioners who can operate in ambiguity.

The third is deeply human relational skill. In healthcare and care-adjacent settings, robots are already being used for logistics and routine support tasks, and there is evidence that this can free staff time for more patient-centred work rather than simply removing the need for people. But that does not mean care becomes less human. If anything, it means the human core of care becomes more visible: reassurance, trust, motivation, emotional attunement, and presence. Colleges that treat empathy as a soft extra will miss the point. In an AI-shaped economy, some of the most defensible skills will be the ones that are technically hard to automate and socially hard to outsource.

The Premium on the Human-Made

There is also a longer-run opportunity that FE should not ignore. As machine-made quality becomes cheaper and more common, genuinely human-made work may become more valuable at the premium end of the market. Bespoke craft, fine food, specialist making, restoration, and creative technical trades could all benefit from a world in which standardised perfection is abundant. Colleges should not bet the institution on that outcome, but neither should they overlook it.

The Strategic Conclusion

So the strategic conclusion is not that FE should retreat from the trades. Quite the opposite. Colleges are right to expand construction and technical capacity now. They are right to build stronger relationships with employers in the physical economy. They are right to treat practical learning as central, not secondary.

But they should not make the mistake universities made with cognitive knowledge: assuming today's scarce capability will remain scarce forever.

The strongest colleges over the next decade will be the ones that do three things at once: meet the immediate demand for practical skills, redesign programmes around human-machine collaboration, and elevate the durable human capabilities that survive both shocks. If they do that, FE will not be the educational sector left behind by AI. It may become the sector most aligned with what the economy actually needs next.`},
  {title:"AI in FE — Why Some Colleges Are Racing Ahead While Others Stall",summary:"A divide is opening in further education between colleges using AI with clear purpose and colleges treating it as a scattered tech experiment. The difference is rarely budget alone; it is leadership, governance and staff confidence.",category:"Education",read_time:"6 minutes",slug:"ai-in-fe-why-some-colleges-are-racing-ahead-while-others-stall",date:"2026-02-18",featured:false,body:`Two colleges can have roughly the same funding pressures, the same policy environment and access to the same AI tools, yet end up in very different places. One has a clear AI policy, small pilots tied to curriculum goals, staff development underway and governors asking the right questions. The other has a few isolated experiments, nervous staff, unclear rules and growing concern that AI is creating more noise than value. That is the real story of AI in FE colleges in 2026: a widening gap between strategic adopters and stalled adopters. And the difference is usually not budget. It is leadership clarity. (Gatsby)
FE Week has put the point bluntly: some colleges are moving quickly, while others are struggling to do much at all, and that gap matters because learners are entering a labour market where AI is already reshaping tasks, roles and expectations. The World Economic Forum says around 40% of employers expect to reduce workforce numbers where AI can automate tasks, even while many plan to hire more people with AI-related skills. Colleges do not need to become technology companies, but they do need a credible plan for how AI affects teaching, assessment, operations and employability. (FE Week)
The fast movers
The colleges making progress are not necessarily the ones buying the most software. They are the ones starting with governance and purpose. Gatsby’s December 2025 report found that FE colleges are already “curious, creative and already experimenting”, with staff trialling AI for planning, feedback, learner support and operational efficiency. But the same report makes clear that effective adoption depends on leadership turning that curiosity into structure. (Gatsby)
In practice, the fast movers tend to do three things well. First, they set clear rules: what AI can be used for, what needs human oversight, and where safeguarding, data protection and assessment integrity sit. Second, they pilot with a reason. They do not ask, “Where can we use AI?” They ask, “Where would AI reduce workload, improve learner support or strengthen curriculum delivery?” Third, they invest in staff development early, because confident staff are the difference between controlled experimentation and low-level chaos. Gatsby identifies limited training, infrastructure constraints and lack of clear guidance as the main blockers, which implies the opposite is also true: where those barriers are addressed, adoption moves faster. (Gatsby)
This is also why governance is becoming more formal. The January 2026 update to the FEA-I model policy for the use of generative AI in colleges explicitly reflects the latest DfE, Ofsted and Ofqual guidance and places stronger emphasis on safeguarding, procurement, high-stakes decision-making and assessment integrity. That is a sign of the sector maturing: successful colleges are moving beyond enthusiasm and into operational discipline. (LinkedIn)
The stalling pattern
The stalling colleges often make the same mistake: they treat AI as a procurement challenge rather than a strategic one. They focus on which platform to buy before they have decided what problem they are solving, what risks they are prepared to manage, or how staff will be supported to use the tools well. The result is predictable. Adoption becomes fragmented. Innovation sits with a few enthusiasts. Staff confidence varies wildly. Leaders cannot easily explain impact. (Gatsby)
That matters because AI does not stay neatly contained in one department. It touches lesson planning, learner support, accessibility, assessment, communications, back-office workflows and employer engagement. If there is no shared purpose, the burden falls on teachers and middle leaders to work it out for themselves. FE Week captured that risk clearly: “Without structure and capacity, AI innovation will become another burden on teachers rather than a driver of better learning.” (FE Week)
There is also an evidence problem. Ofsted’s 2024/25 annual report said there is still a gap in research around the impact of AI on outcomes, and that only a small proportion of inspectors who had seen AI on inspection felt providers were using it in ways that improved outcomes. That should not be read as a case against AI. It should be read as a warning against shallow implementation. Colleges that cannot show why they are using AI, where it helps, and how they monitor the downside are much more likely to stall. (GOV.UK)
The policy pressure building
The policy environment is also getting harder to ignore. In January 2026, the Education Secretary announced £23 million to expand the government’s EdTech Testbeds pilot, and the February 2026 white paper confirmed that the programme will run over four years in schools and colleges to build evidence on tools that reduce workload, improve outcomes and support inclusion. That does two things at once: it creates opportunity for proactive institutions, and it raises the bar for leaders who still want to treat AI as a side issue. (GOV.UK)
The same direction of travel appears in product safety. The DfE’s January 2026 Generative AI Product Safety Standards now set out the safeguards AI products should meet to be considered safe for use in educational settings, including protections around cognitive development, emotional safeguarding and teacher oversight. Colleges may not all be building their own AI tools, but they are absolutely responsible for deciding what they allow into their classrooms and systems. (GOV.UK)
Sector voices are reading these signals clearly. FE News argued this month that the next phase of AI policy in education will depend on strong governance, meaningful AI literacy and purposeful engagement with EdTech Testbeds. Even where specific reforms are school-led, the direction is obvious enough that FE providers cannot afford to wait for a bespoke instruction manual. (FE News)
The risk of adding work, not removing it
This is the central leadership test. AI should reduce friction, not add another layer of it. Yet that is exactly what happens when colleges introduce tools without workflows, permissions, training or evaluation. Staff start double-checking poor outputs, creating their own unofficial rules, or avoiding the tools altogether. What was sold as efficiency becomes one more thing to manage. (FE Week)
The labour-market context makes that failure more costly. FE Week notes a surge in colleges advertising digital leadership and support roles to develop infrastructure and staff capability. At the same time, employers are shifting quickly: the World Economic Forum says many expect job redesign, more AI-skilled hiring and significant automation of routine tasks by 2030. If colleges do not build coherent internal capability now, they risk falling behind both as educators and as employers themselves. (FE Week)
How to start
The answer is not to rush into a dozen pilots at once. It is to get the basics right.
Start with a governance framework. Decide who owns AI strategy, how risks are reviewed, how safeguarding and assessment integrity are protected, and what principles governors expect leaders to follow. The strongest colleges make AI a leadership issue first and a technology issue second. (LinkedIn)
Then nominate an AI champion or small cross-functional group with enough authority to join up curriculum, quality, IT, safeguarding and staff development. Gatsby’s findings suggest colleges already have plenty of curiosity; what many lack is the organisational capacity to turn experimentation into a coherent programme. (Gatsby)
Finally, run a diagnostic before you buy more tools. Find out where staff confidence is low, where current use is happening off-policy, where learner-facing risks sit, and where AI could actually remove workload rather than add to it. That is the point at which strategy becomes practical. (FE News)
The FE divide on AI is real, but it is not fixed. Colleges that are racing ahead are not magically freer, richer or less busy. They are clearer. They know what they are trying to achieve, how they will govern it, and how they will bring staff with them. If you want a companion piece to this, see Provio’s Why Every College Needs an AI Strategy Before Ofsted Expects One. And if you want to understand where your own college stands, Provio’s 9-section Education AI Readiness Diagnostic is the practical starting point. It helps turn uncertainty into a roadmap before the gap widens further.`},
  {title:"How SMEs Can Escape the AI “Fumble Period”",summary:"More UK SMEs are using AI every day, but many still feel little has become easier. The problem is rarely the tool itself; it is the messy gap between adoption and operational integration.",category:"Business",read_time:"5 minutes",slug:"how-smes-can-escape-the-ai-fumble-period",date:"2026-02-21",featured:false,body:`You bought the AI tools. Your team has tried them. A few people say they save time. But the business as a whole does not feel lighter, faster or more joined up. That is the AI fumble period: the awkward stage where adoption is rising, but value is not yet flowing. It is becoming a defining issue for SME AI adoption in the UK. Employment Hero describes it as the gap between buying a tool and learning to use it effectively, and argues that for many businesses this period is currently creating more friction than benefit. (Employment Hero)
The backdrop makes that especially important. The UK economy grew by just 0.1%, and SMEs are under pressure to find productivity gains without adding headcount or cost. At the same time, British Chambers of Commerce research shows that 35% of SMEs are now actively using AI, up from 25% in 2024. Another 24% plan to adopt it, while the share with no plans has fallen from 43% to 33%. On paper, that looks encouraging. In practice, it means a growing number of firms are now entering the same messy middle phase at once. (Employment Hero)
The fumble period, explained
The simplest way to understand the fumble period is this: a business adds fast AI tools to slow human processes. Staff use chatbots, copilots or automated features in bits and pieces, but the underlying workflow stays the same. So instead of removing effort, AI gets layered on top of it. People rewrite prompts, fact-check weak outputs, move information manually between systems and keep separate “just in case” processes running alongside the new tools. That is not transformation. It is duplication. (Employment Hero)
The British Chambers of Commerce data shows exactly why this happens. Although AI usage is rising, only 11% of firms say they are using technology to a “great extent” to automate or streamline operations. Many more say they are using it only to some extent, minimally or not at all. Air IT’s analysis of the same BCC data makes the point clearly: adoption numbers look positive, but far fewer SMEs are using AI to change how the business actually runs. (British Chambers of Commerce)
The £25 billion drag
This is not just a feeling problem. Employment Hero points to research, cited from Starling Bank, suggesting disconnected tools and poor integration cost the UK economy £25.3 billion a year, with staff spending around 15 hours a week manually bridging gaps between apps. That is the hidden cost of digital fragmentation: not a lack of software, but too many systems that do not work cleanly together. (Employment Hero)
QuickBooks’ January 2026 UK SME survey shows the same pattern from another angle. Nearly 2 in 5 owners say poor tech integration is creating inefficiencies. 59% still use spreadsheets in financial management, 52% say inflation and rising costs remain their top external challenge, and 51% say cash flow is currently a problem. When margins are tight, that kind of operational friction matters more, not less. (QuickBooks)
The pressure extends into people management too. QuickBooks found that 34% of SMEs say finding new talent is becoming harder and 32% report similar difficulty retaining existing employees. That matters because when talent is scarce, businesses cannot afford to waste skilled people on avoidable admin, app-switching and AI clean-up work. (QuickBooks)
Why it’s not a software problem
This is why the answer is not “buy a better AI tool.” The core issue is usually process clarity. Employment Hero’s Russell Dias argues that adoption often stalls when the expected downside, such as getting something wrong, breaching compliance or simply not knowing how to start, feels bigger than the time saved. That is a governance and confidence problem, not just a technology problem. (Employment Hero)
The strongest clue is that ambition is still high. QuickBooks reports that 77% of UK SME owners want to grow, while AI use is becoming routine for many firms. But wanting growth and achieving it are different things. AI only helps when businesses define what good usage looks like in each workflow, who reviews outputs, what data can be used, and where the tool fits in the process rather than floating around outside it. (QuickBooks)
Three steps out of the fumble period
The first step is to make the rules crystal clear. Set out which tools are approved, what data should never be entered, what human review is required and where AI is useful versus off-limits. Employment Hero is right that cutting through the noise on privacy, IP and compliance helps staff move from hesitation to confident use. (Employment Hero)
The second step is to focus on workflow integration, not tool accumulation. Air IT notes that many SMEs use AI for content, admin, research and everyday speed-ups, but that is not the same as using it to redesign service delivery or remove manual effort. The real gains come when AI is tied into one specific process at a time, such as proposal drafting, invoice chasing, scheduling, customer support triage or internal reporting. (airit.co.uk)
The third step is to assess skills and usage honestly. The BCC’s own message is that many SMEs are plugging into AI without yet using it to full effect. That means leaders need to know where power users already exist, where staff are improvising, and where adoption is superficial. Once you can see the friction clearly, it becomes much easier to remove it. (British Chambers of Commerce)
The AI fumble period is normal, but it is not harmless. Left unmanaged, it becomes a tax on time, confidence and productivity. Managed properly, it becomes the awkward middle stage before real operational gains. If you want a companion piece to this, read Provio’s The AI Skills Boost — Is Free Training Enough? And if you want to identify exactly where the friction sits in your own business, start with Provio’s Business AI Readiness survey. It gives SME leaders a practical picture of where AI is helping, where it is stalling, and what needs to change next. (Employment Hero)`},
  {title:"Robotics in Construction — Why the West Midlands Needs a Skills Pipeline Now",summary:"Construction robotics is no longer a future concept. With government backing adoption hubs and the UK trying to close a major robotics gap, the West Midlands needs a skills pipeline now if it wants to capture the opportunity.",category:"Sector Spotlight",read_time:"5 minutes",slug:"robotics-in-construction-why-the-west-midlands-needs-a-skills-pipeline-now",date:"2026-02-25",featured:false,body:`Robotic arms building timber homes in Oxfordshire are not a thought experiment anymore. They are already operating in live UK production environments, helping manufacturers produce housing components faster, with less labour intensity and more precision. That matters for the West Midlands because the question is no longer whether construction robotics in the UK is coming. It is whether regions like ours will have the technicians, supervisors and employer-education partnerships needed to benefit from it when adoption accelerates. Reuters’ reporting from August 2025 shows that robotics is already being used in modern timber-frame production, while government has now committed £40 million to a new network of Robotics Adoption Hubs. (Reuters)
The opportunity is large, but so is the gap. The UK is still well behind comparable markets in construction robotics use. ING estimates there were just 0.5 robots per 10,000 construction workers in the UK in 2023, compared with 1.5 in Europe and 0.6 in the United States. At the same time, the labour challenge is getting worse: Reuters reports that about a fifth of UK construction workers are over 50, and 25% of those are expected to retire in the coming decade. In other words, construction is trying to modernise while also replacing an ageing workforce. (Reuters)
The automation accelerating in construction
The technology is broader than many people realise. CCBP notes that robotics in construction is already appearing in bricklaying, rebar placement, excavation, plastering and modular production. Construction Job Board UK points to the growing use of AI-driven planning systems, autonomous drones for inspections, robotic bricklayers, robotic demolition, and automated factory processes in prefabrication. This is not a single machine story; it is a workflow story that runs from design and scheduling through to fabrication, inspection and high-risk site activity. (CCBP)
That is why off-site and modular production matter so much. CCBP argues that bringing work to controlled factory environments can overcome many of the barriers that slow direct on-site automation, while still delivering speed, quality and safety gains when components are assembled on location. Reuters’ Oxfordshire example backs that up: Donaldson Timber Systems says its robotics-supported system can reduce build time by around 10 weeks compared with traditional materials. (CCBP)
The UK’s robotics gap
The UK’s problem is not imagination. It is adoption. Government’s Technology Adoption Review 2025 says UK firms still face major barriers around use-case understanding, integration with legacy systems, finance and confidence in the practical value of technologies like robotics. That review specifically suggested new adoption hubs for Robotics and Autonomous Systems to de-risk uptake, showcase real-world applications and connect firms with expertise. The government has since moved on that recommendation, confirming £40 million for a new network of Robotics Adoption Hubs. (GOV.UK)
The upside for construction is substantial. CCBP, citing a GOV.UK independent report, says current automation in UK construction is generating around £0.1 billion in economic output, but if potential automation rates are achieved by 2035 that could rise to £46.8 billion. Even allowing for uncertainty, the direction is clear: construction automation is still at an early stage, and regions that build capability early will be in a much better position than those that treat it as someone else’s problem. (CCBP)
The West Midlands opportunity
This is where the West Midlands has a genuine opening. The region already has strengths that map well onto construction robotics: advanced manufacturing capability, major infrastructure experience, FE colleges, universities, and a supply-chain footprint linked to large projects. CCBP highlights Nationally Significant Infrastructure Projects such as HS2 as major opportunities for trialling and scaling robotics in live environments. For the West Midlands, that is not abstract. It is directly relevant to the region’s infrastructure and built-environment ecosystem. (CCBP)
There is also a housing and productivity case. Reuters notes that the UK is still trying to reach 300,000 new homes a year, a level England has not achieved since the 1970s. If robotics, modular construction and AI-enabled planning can help close that delivery gap, then regions that can supply the people to implement those systems will have a strategic advantage. (Reuters)
And there is a talent story too. Robotics is not only about replacing labour. It can help attract new labour. Reuters reports that automated factories have drawn more interest from tech-savvy younger workers, with one manufacturing director saying the technology encourages young people to consider the sector as a career. In a separate Reuters report, City of Westminster College said enrolments in engineering, construction and built environment courses rose 9.6% over three years, partly linked to AI-era career anxieties and the appeal of more future-proof, hands-on pathways. (Reuters)
The skills pipeline challenge
This is the real bottleneck. Who trains the robotics technicians, automation supervisors, drone inspection specialists and site robotics coordinators? CCBP is explicit that the barriers are not only technical. They include capital costs, site variability, regulatory safety certification, and a skills gap in robotics implementation and maintenance. It also points to the Robotics Growth Partnership’s call for a national skills pipeline stretching from technicians to specialist engineers. (CCBP)
That means the West Midlands cannot rely on technology diffusion alone. Colleges need clearer employer input. Employers need to signal what roles are emerging. SME contractors need access not just to equipment but to shared training routes and advisory support. Otherwise the risk is simple: robotics investment arrives, but the region lacks the people to install, supervise, maintain and improve the systems. (CCBP)
The answer is coordinated action now. Construction employers should define the digital and automation roles they expect to need over the next three to five years. FE providers should map those needs into curriculum and short-course design. Regional leaders should connect housing, infrastructure and skills planning instead of treating them as separate agendas. If you want a related funding angle, see Provio’s What the Growth and Skills Levy Means for SMEs. And if you want to understand where your organisation sits in the shift from interest to implementation, Provio’s Business AI Readiness survey is the right place to start. It helps employers identify the capability gaps that stand between robotics ambition and actual adoption.`},
  {title:"The West Midlands Skills Landscape — Where the Opportunities Are in 2026",summary:"The West Midlands enters 2026 with the UK’s highest regional unemployment rate and a sharp rise in youth claimants. But the region also has unusual strengths: devolved powers, active university partnerships, skills funding reform and clear growth sectors for organisations ready to move.",category:"Regional / Policy",read_time:"6 minutes",slug:"the-west-midlands-skills-landscape-where-the-opportunities-are-in-2026",date:"2026-02-28",featured:false,body:`The headline number is stark: the West Midlands unemployment rate stands at 6.2%, the highest of any UK region going into 2026. On its own, that tells a difficult story. But the fuller West Midlands skills landscape in 2026 is more nuanced than a single labour-market figure suggests. The region is under real strain, especially on youth employment, yet it also has something many other regions do not: a meaningful combination of devolved powers, targeted skills strategy, active university-business collaboration, and new national funding mechanisms that could genuinely shift outcomes if employers, colleges and policymakers act strategically. (Yotru)
The challenge
Start with the basics. Yotru’s February 2026 regional labour-market analysis puts West Midlands unemployment at 6.2% in Q4 2025, up 1.9 percentage points year on year. It also reports that the region’s employment rate fell to 72.7%, down 1.5 percentage points quarter on quarter, which was one of the sharpest quarterly falls in the country. Express & Star’s reporting on the same labour-market picture has repeatedly described the region as the worst-affected in the UK on unemployment measures through late 2025 and early 2026. (Yotru)
The claimant picture is just as serious. Across the wider WMCA area, Yotru reports 148,505 claimants, up 18.4% year on year, with 27,735 youth claimants aged 18 to 24, up 12.1%. That matters because claimant growth is not just a lagging measure of hardship; it is a live signal that the region is carrying a growing stock of people who need routes back into work, training or progression. For colleges, careers teams and employers, this is not a background condition. It is the operating environment. (Yotru)
This is why the West Midlands should not be discussed only in terms of “economic challenge.” It is a skills coordination challenge too. A region can have vacancies, investment and growth sectors on paper, but still struggle if residents are not being connected clearly enough to those opportunities, if employers cannot articulate their skills needs, or if training systems remain fragmented. WMCA’s own Employment and Skills Strategy 2024–27 makes exactly that point: the region needs a more integrated employment and skills ecosystem because the current system is too confusing for residents and employers and not aligned tightly enough to local labour-market need. (wmca.org.uk)
The devolution advantage
This is where the region’s opportunity begins. The West Midlands Deeper Devolution Deal, estimated at around £1.5 billion, gives the region greater influence over skills, careers, employment support and related investment decisions. That does not solve labour-market weakness by itself, but it does mean the West Midlands has more room than many places to shape a locally relevant response instead of waiting for one-size-fits-all national fixes. (wmca.org.uk)
WMCA’s Employment and Skills Strategy is designed as part of that devolved architecture. It explicitly positions skills policy as a blueprint for investment and ties employment support much more directly to regional economic growth, business need and community outcomes. In other words, this is not just about helping people find any job. It is about building a regional system that is more responsive to where the economy is actually going. (wmca.org.uk)
That matters because the national policy backdrop is increasingly aligned with regional action. The UK’s Industrial Strategy now identifies eight growth-driving sectors for long-term support, and the West Midlands regional version of that strategy frames the area’s opportunity in relation to frontier industries and high-growth sectors rather than simply recovery alone. For a region with strong manufacturing, professional services, transport links, universities and growing digital infrastructure, that creates a more credible foundation for targeted skills planning. (Business Growth Service)
Where the opportunities are
The opportunity side of the story is easiest to see in digital and technology skills. Greater Birmingham Chambers recently highlighted that 18% of UK adults — around 7.5 million people — lack the essential digital skills needed for work. That is a national figure, but the regional relevance is obvious: any area trying to raise employment, productivity and business competitiveness will need to close that gap quickly. (greaterbirminghamchambers.com)
The West Midlands digital economy is already pointing in that direction. techUK’s West Midlands work says the region faces increasing demand for intermediate and advanced digital skills, and TechWM has similarly warned that the local digital skills shortage threatens growth unless the ecosystem becomes more joined up. That means digital capability is no longer a niche agenda for tech firms; it is a mainstream employability and business-productivity issue across the region. (TechUK)
There are also encouraging signs of practical collaboration. In March 2026, the University of Wolverhampton highlighted a regional initiative bringing West Midlands universities together to help SMEs build AI and cyber skills, including a “Gen AI Masterclass for Small Businesses.” That kind of partnership matters because it links three groups that are too often treated separately: universities, employers and the regional business base. It is exactly the kind of connective tissue the West Midlands needs more of. (University of Wolverhampton)
WMCA’s wider growth planning reinforces the same direction. Its regional growth plan and related strategies emphasise increasing the skills base, reducing economic inactivity and supporting sectors where manufacturing, digital, robotics and green technologies are changing what jobs look like. This is important because the region’s opportunities are not all in one place. They sit across advanced manufacturing, digital and cyber, construction, health-related innovation, clean growth and professional services. (West Midlands Growth Plan |)
How the Growth & Skills Levy helps the region
The other major opportunity in 2026 is the Growth & Skills Levy. For the West Midlands, this matters not only because of policy reform but because it could directly improve access to training in a region with high youth claimant numbers and strong SME demand. From April 2026, eligible under-25 apprentices at SMEs will have their training costs fully funded, removing the old employer co-investment barrier. At the same time, employers will be able to use levy funding for the first wave of short modular apprenticeship units in areas including digital, advanced AI and engineering. (find-employer-schemes.education.gov.uk)
That is a big deal regionally. The West Midlands has a large SME base, persistent youth employment pressure and clear demand for technical and digital capability. A funding system that makes under-25 training easier to access and supports shorter, faster routes into priority skills could be unusually valuable here. It will not fix the region on its own, but it creates a much better mechanism for turning employer demand into actual entry routes for younger people. (Yotru)
What employers and colleges should do
The region’s challenge in 2026 is not lack of activity. It is lack of alignment. Employers should start by auditing where they are short of skills now and where demand is moving next, especially in digital, AI, engineering and construction-linked roles. Colleges and training providers should be asking not only what programmes they already offer, but whether those programmes map cleanly to the sectors and capabilities the region is prioritising. And policymakers should keep pushing for local systems that are simpler to navigate for young people and smaller employers. (wmca.org.uk)
The West Midlands does have genuine reasons for optimism. It has the highest regional unemployment rate in the UK, yes. But it also has devolved powers, a serious skills strategy, active institutions, and a labour market where targeted action could make a visible difference quite quickly. The organisations that benefit most in 2026 will be the ones that read both sides of the picture at once: the urgency of the challenge and the reality of the opportunity. For a companion piece, see Provio’s Youth Unemployment at 16.1% — What the Data Really Tells Us or What the Growth and Skills Levy Means for SMEs. And if you want to understand where your organisation stands in this regional shift, Provio’s Business AI Readiness survey is a practical place to start. It helps employers and partners see where skills gaps, digital readiness and opportunity are really sitting across the organisation.`},
  {title:"What the Growth and Skills Levy Means for SMEs",summary:"The Growth and Skills Levy is the biggest rethink of employer-funded training since 2017. For SMEs, it creates a real opening — but only for those who understand the new rules early.",category:"Business",read_time:"5 minutes",slug:"what-the-growth-and-skills-levy-means-for-smes",date:"2026-03-01",featured:false,body:`The Growth and Skills Levy is the biggest rethink of employer-funded training since the levy system arrived in 2017. In plain English, it means this: from 2026, skills funding becomes more flexible, more targeted at younger talent, and more urgent to use well. For SMEs, that creates a real opening. Businesses that understand the new rules early will be able to hire and train faster, reduce some upfront cost barriers, and build stronger pipelines in areas where skills are hardest to find. The businesses that wait may miss the window, lose funding opportunities, or end up paying more than they expected. (ise.org.uk)
What’s actually changing
There are four headline changes every SME owner and HR leader should understand.
First, eligible apprentices under 25 at SMEs will have their training costs fully covered by government. That removes the old 5% co-investment requirement that smaller employers previously had to pay for most non-levy-funded apprenticeships. Government and regional business guidance both present this as a major move to make it easier for smaller firms to recruit young talent. (GOV.UK)
Second, the levy becomes more flexible. From April 2026, government says new short courses in areas such as AI, engineering and digital will begin rolling out, alongside a new Level 4 AI apprenticeship. Current employer briefings also indicate that up to 50% of levy funds may be usable on short modular “apprenticeship units,” with some units lasting as little as one week, although some delivery details are still emerging. Skills4Stem and ISE both describe this as a move toward more modular, employer-responsive training. (GOV.UK)
Third, levy funds will expire faster. The old 24-month window is being cut to 12 months. That sounds technical, but the practical meaning is simple: training plans can no longer sit on the shelf. Employers will need tighter planning cycles, clearer ownership, and faster decision-making around where money should go. (find-employer-schemes.education.gov.uk)
Fourth, overspending gets more expensive. Once a levy-paying employer has used up its pot, the government co-investment rate drops from 95% to 75%, meaning the employer pays 25% rather than 5%. For larger levy payers this sharply raises the cost of poor planning; for SMEs receiving transferred funding or working in the same ecosystem, it will likely make access to unused levy funds more competitive and more strategically managed. (find-employer-schemes.education.gov.uk)
Why this is a windfall for SMEs
For smaller employers, the biggest upside is obvious: free training for eligible under-25 apprentices. If you have avoided apprenticeships because even a small co-investment felt like one more cost, this reform changes the equation. It lowers the barrier to bringing in school leavers, college leavers and early-career hires, especially in roles where attitude, potential and trainability matter as much as experience. (GOV.UK)
The second upside is flexibility. Traditional apprenticeships can be brilliant, but they do not always fit immediate business needs. The new modular approach is designed to help employers tackle narrower capability gaps in faster-moving fields, especially digital, engineering and AI. For an SME, that could mean building a skills plan around real operational problems rather than waiting for a full programme to fit the moment. (GOV.UK)
There is also a labour-cost nuance worth understanding. From April 2026, the apprentice minimum wage rises to £8.00 an hour, so apprentices are not “cheap labour” and should not be viewed that way. But for apprentices under 25 on approved standards who earn below £50,270, employers do not pay Class 1 employer National Insurance contributions. For SMEs, that softens the total employment cost and improves the business case for bringing in younger apprentices. (GOV.UK)
And the backdrop matters. Apprenticeship starts were 503,700 in 2015/16. They fell to 339,580 in 2023/24, a drop of 164,120, before recovering modestly to 353,500 in 2024/25. That means the system is still around 150,000 starts below 2015/16 levels. Government is reforming the levy because the old model did not produce enough of the outcomes it wanted, particularly for younger people. SMEs that move early stand to benefit from a system now being deliberately rebalanced in their favour.
The catch
This is not free money with no strings attached.
The first catch is the new 12-month expiry rule. If funds move through employer accounts faster, skills planning has to move faster too. Businesses that leave training decisions to year-end reviews or occasional conversations will be more likely to waste value. (find-employer-schemes.education.gov.uk)
The second catch is that some operational detail is still settling. ISE has noted that employers should expect more clarity on areas such as unit costs, training hours and levy rules as rollout continues. That does not mean businesses should wait. It means they should prepare now, so they are ready when the final detail lands. (ise.org.uk)
What to do now
1. Audit your skills gaps. Focus first on the roles that are hardest to recruit for, the capabilities slowing growth, and the areas where AI, digital or technical upskilling could have the fastest impact. Do not start with the funding pot. Start with the business problem. (ise.org.uk)
2. Register on the Apprenticeship Service. All apprenticeships in England are managed through the apprenticeship service, and employers need an account to access funding and manage apprenticeships. If you are not set up, you are not really in position to act. (GOV.UK)
3. Identify under-25 hiring opportunities now. Look at entry-level vacancies, succession gaps and departments where junior talent could be developed quickly. The combination of full training funding, no employer NICs in many cases, and new modular options makes this the best SME apprenticeship opportunity in years. (GOV.UK)
The Growth and Skills Levy is not just a policy rename. It is a shift in who the system is for, how fast employers must act, and how flexibly training can be used. For SMEs, that is a genuine advantage if they move now. At Provio, we help make changes like this simple. Our Business AI Readiness survey helps SME leaders identify where skills gaps sit today, where AI and digital capability matter most, and how to turn policy change into a smarter workforce plan rather than another line in the HR inbox.`},
  {title:"Why Every College Needs an AI Strategy Before Ofsted Expects One",summary:"Ofsted will not ask for your AI strategy. But AI now shows up in every area inspectors examine. A college without an AI strategy is a college without a coherent answer when those questions arise.",category:"Education",read_time:"6 minutes",slug:"why-every-college-needs-an-ai-strategy-before-ofsted-expects-one",date:"2026-03-03",featured:false,body:`Ofsted is not going to walk into a college and ask, “Do you have an AI strategy?” In fact, Ofsted’s own guidance says inspectors do not look at AI as a standalone part of inspection and do not require providers to use AI at all. But that is exactly why this matters. AI now shows up indirectly in the places inspectors already examine: leadership decision-making, curriculum, safeguarding, data protection, homework and coursework policies, and the wider experiences of learners. In practice, a college without an AI strategy is a college without a coherent answer when those questions arise. (GOV.UK)
What the new inspection framework actually looks for
The first thing to understand is that the inspection landscape has changed. Since November 2025, Ofsted has dropped the old single-word overall judgement and moved to report cards with a five-point scale: exceptional, strong standard, expected standard, needs attention, and urgent improvement. Safeguarding is reported separately as met or not met. For FE and skills, inspections now look across multiple evaluation areas, including leadership and governance, inclusion, safeguarding, contribution to meeting skills needs in colleges, and provision-level areas such as curriculum, teaching and training, achievement, and participation and development. (GOV.UK)
That matters because the new framework is more evidence-rich and more granular. Ofsted’s FE operating guide makes clear that inspections are built through leadership meetings, learning walks, conversations during visits to learning environments, and planned discussions with learners and apprentices. Learning walks are described as an important way for leaders to show inspectors the provider’s context, while learner conversations are part of the evidence base inspectors rely on. In other words, inspection is now less about a headline label and more about whether leaders can show clear rationale, sound implementation and visible impact. (GOV.UK)
Where AI now appears in inspection
This is where many colleges misread the situation. Ofsted says it will not inspect AI in isolation, but it can consider the impact of AI on children and learners wherever that impact matters. Inspectors may ask leaders how AI use supports learners’ best interests, and may look at provider policies on learners’ use of AI in lessons, at home, and in homework or coursework assignments. Ofsted also says AI-related risks can be considered through existing inspection lenses such as safeguarding, data protection, bias and discrimination. So while “AI strategy” is not a separate line on the scorecard, weak AI governance can still show up across several lines of it. (GOV.UK)
For colleges, the most obvious inspection touchpoints are curriculum intent, safeguarding and digital capability. If a college says it is preparing learners for modern workplaces, inspectors can reasonably expect leaders to have thought about where AI belongs in the curriculum, how staff model safe use, and how learners are taught to use these tools critically rather than passively. FE sector commentary has been blunt on this point: government expects FE to be proactive on AI, not lagging behind. The Gatsby Foundation’s late-2025 report paints a similar picture: colleges are increasingly curious and open-minded, but progress is still being held back by limited staff training, unclear policies, variable infrastructure and lack of time. (FE Week)
The DfE standards shift
The pressure has increased again because the Department for Education updated its Generative AI Product Safety Standards on 19 January 2026. The title change matters, but the substance matters more. The DfE now sets out minimum expected safeguards for education-facing AI products, especially learner-facing ones. These include rules designed to protect cognitive development: products should not provide final answers, full solutions or complete worked examples by default; they should use progressive disclosure, prompt learner input first, and only show a full solution after a genuine learner attempt. (GOV.UK)
The standards also go well beyond plagiarism concerns. On emotional and social development, the DfE says developers should not anthropomorphise AI products or imply emotion, consciousness, personhood or agency. Products should avoid trying to build pseudo-relationships with learners, should remind users that AI cannot replace human relationships, and should include default time limits plus hard limits that can only be reset by a teacher or administrator. On mental health, products should detect indicators of learner distress, follow appropriate escalation pathways and direct learners toward human support. (GOV.UK)
Strictly speaking, these standards are aimed at edtech developers and suppliers, not as a statutory AI duty imposed directly on colleges. But colleges are explicitly identified as users who may rely on them when deciding which products are safe for education. So the practical implication is straightforward: if your college is procuring or approving AI tools without mapping them against these standards, your governance is already behind the curve. (GOV.UK)
Three things to do this term
1. Put a governance framework in place.
Every college should have a simple, board-visible AI governance structure this term: approved principles, named owners, procurement checks, a register of current use cases, and a risk review process linked to safeguarding, data protection and assessment. Sector practice is moving this way already. The January 2026 update to the FEA-I model policy was explicitly framed around the latest DfE, Ofsted and Ofqual guidance, with added emphasis on safeguarding, procurement, high-stakes decision-making and assessment integrity. (LinkedIn)
2. Launch an AI literacy programme for leaders, staff and governors.
A strategy is useless if only one digital lead understands it. FE News recently argued that institutions need strong governance and meaningful AI literacy now, while Gatsby’s FE research found that staff interest is growing but confidence, training and infrastructure remain uneven. The colleges that get ahead will not be the ones with the most AI tools; they will be the ones where principals, curriculum leaders, DSLs, governors and teaching staff share a common baseline understanding of risk, pedagogy and opportunity. (FE News)
3. Create a learning integrity policy, not just an “AI allowed/not allowed” rule.
Colleges need clearer rules for coursework, homework, drafting, feedback, authorship and verification. Ofqual’s 2026 guide for schools and colleges says unacknowledged use of AI tools can amount to malpractice. Ofsted, meanwhile, says inspectors may look at policies governing learner AI use in lessons, at home and in coursework. That means colleges need something more sophisticated than blanket prohibition: they need clear permitted uses, declaration expectations, staff guidance and assessment designs that still verify what learners know and can do. (GOV.UK)
The colleges that treat AI as a side issue will find it turning up everywhere at once: in curriculum conversations, learner expectations, safeguarding decisions, procurement questions and inspection evidence. The colleges that move now can turn the same issue into an advantage. They can show that leadership is in control, that staff are confident, and that learners are being prepared for a world where AI is normal but not ungoverned. Provio’s Education AI Readiness Diagnostic is the best place to start: a practical way to assess governance, capability, curriculum readiness and risk before inspection pressure exposes the gaps.`},
  {title:"Youth Unemployment at 16.1% — What the Data Really Tells Us",summary:"UK youth unemployment has climbed to its highest level in more than a decade, and the West Midlands is carrying a disproportionate share of the strain. The data points to a regional challenge that education providers, employers and policymakers can only solve together.",category:"Regional / Policy",read_time:"6 minutes",slug:"youth-unemployment-at-161-what-the-data-really-tells-us",date:"2026-03-04",featured:false,body:`The headline figure is hard to ignore: UK youth unemployment for 16 to 24-year-olds reached 16.1% in Q4 2025, the highest since early 2015. At the same time, overall UK unemployment rose to 5.2%, its highest level since the three months to January 2021 and the highest outside the pandemic period for more than a decade. That matters because youth unemployment is not just a smaller version of general unemployment. It is usually an early warning signal that entry routes into the labour market are weakening. When that happens, the damage can last longer for younger people than for the economy as a whole. (Express & Star)
There is also a broader European warning sign in the data. Resolution Foundation commentary, quoted by Express & Star, said the UK’s youth unemployment rate had moved above the EU average of 14.9%, a striking reversal from the long-run pattern. Full Fact later noted that comparable OECD series show the UK first moved clearly above the EU average in Q3 2025, while some quarter-by-quarter EU comparisons for Q4 were still being clarified. Either way, the direction is clear: the UK has shifted from outperforming Europe on youth unemployment to lagging it. (Express & Star)
The West Midlands picture
This matters everywhere, but it matters especially in the West Midlands youth unemployment 2026 story. Regional labour-market data shows the West Midlands entered 2026 with 6.2% unemployment, the highest of any UK region. Its employment rate fell to 72.7%, down 1.5 percentage points quarter on quarter, which Yotru described as one of the sharpest falls in the country. The region is not just sharing in a national slowdown; it is at the sharp end of it. (Yotru)
The claimant figures make the pressure even clearer. Across the WMCA area, there were 148,505 claimants, up 18.4% year on year, and 27,735 youth claimants aged 18 to 24, up 12.1%. Those are not abstract percentages. They point to a growing pool of young people who need an entry route, a second chance, or a more credible bridge between education and work than the current system is offering. (Yotru)
For education leaders and careers advisers, that regional picture matters because it changes the urgency. In a tighter labour market, weak transitions become more punishing. The same student who might once have found a first job through retail, hospitality, temp work or junior office roles now faces a thinner market, stronger competition and more screening. In the West Midlands, that pressure is compounded by the fact that the region’s labour-market base is already under strain. (Yotru)
Why this downturn hits young people hardest
McKinsey’s recent UK analysis is useful here because it explains why youth unemployment behaves differently from overall unemployment. Historically, it says, youth unemployment tends to rise faster and recover more slowly than the headline rate. Young people are more likely to be in temporary work, more concentrated in cyclical sectors, and less established in the labour market when hiring slows. That makes them easier not to hire, easier not to retain and slower to bring back in once conditions improve. (McKinsey & Company)
That pattern fits the current moment. Entry-level recruitment has weakened, employer costs have risen, and some of the most exposed roles are the kinds of routine and junior tasks that organisations are now redesigning or automating. It would be too simple to say AI is the whole story, because it is not. But it is part of the pressure mix, especially where firms are reducing junior administrative, digital or back-office opportunities while expecting remaining candidates to arrive with stronger technical and workflow skills from day one. (McKinsey & Company)
There is also evidence that some young people are responding by moving away from traditional white-collar routes altogether. Reuters reported in December 2025 that worries about AI-related job disruption, combined with debt concerns and university costs, are pushing some young workers towards skilled trades. One FE provider cited by Reuters said enrolments in engineering, construction and built-environment courses had risen 9.6% over three years. That is not a rejection of higher education across the board. It is a sign that young people are adapting to a labour market that feels less certain and more selective. (Reuters)
The graduate paradox
This is where the story becomes more uncomfortable. The labour market is still telling young people that qualifications matter, but it is also telling many of them that qualifications alone are not enough. McKinsey notes that in the England and Wales Census 2021, nearly 30% of graduates aged 24 or under were working in low-skilled jobs. That means a substantial share of young graduates are not moving straight into graduate-level work at all. They are starting in retail, hospitality, care or other roles that do not make full use of the credential they were told would open doors. (McKinsey & Company)
At the same time, the graduate hiring market is getting tighter. The ISE reported an 8% drop in graduate hiring in the latest cycle, with a further 7% fall forecast, and especially severe weakness in Digital & IT, where vacancies were expected to fall by 53%. So young people are being told that the future belongs to digital and AI-enabled work, while the routes into those careers are shrinking and employers are raising the bar on what “job ready” now means. (ise.org.uk)
That is the real graduate paradox of youth unemployment data UK 2026. Employers increasingly want candidates who understand AI tools, verification, judgment and workflow discipline, but many degrees were not designed to teach those things explicitly. The result is a mismatch: employers saying they need capability, young people presenting credentials, and both sides feeling the other is not quite ready. (McKinsey & Company)
What needs to happen now
The answer is not one intervention. It is coordination. Employers need clearer partnerships with colleges, universities and training providers so entry-level routes match real demand. Education providers need to embed practical AI literacy, employability and sector-specific digital skills rather than treating them as optional extras. And policymakers need to use the new Growth & Skills Levy more strategically, especially in regions like the West Midlands where fully funded under-25 apprenticeship training at SMEs could make a real difference to labour-market entry. (Yotru)
The West Midlands does not just need more programmes. It needs better alignment between what young people are taught, what employers actually need, and where the region is trying to grow. That is why diagnostics matter. For a regional companion piece, see Provio’s The West Midlands Skills Landscape — Where the Opportunities Are in 2026. And if you want to understand where your organisation sits in this challenge, Provio’s diagnostics are designed to act as the bridge between education providers, young people and employers: showing where the gaps really are, and where coordinated action will have the greatest effect.`},
  {title:"What Employers Really Want in 2026 — AI Literacy Is Now a Hiring Filter",summary:"Recruitment has shifted fast. In 2026, candidates are not just competing on qualifications and polish, but on whether they can show responsible, practical AI literacy in a hiring market that is getting tighter and more automated.",category:"Business",read_time:"5 minutes",slug:"what-employers-really-want-in-2026-ai-literacy-is-now-a-hiring-filter",date:"2026-03-05",featured:false,body:`A candidate can now be rejected for talking about AI in the wrong way just as easily as for not mentioning it at all. That is the new reality of the AI literacy hiring filter in 2026. Employers are not simply asking, "Can this person use ChatGPT?" They are asking whether a candidate understands where AI helps, where it misleads, when humans need to stay in control, and how outputs should be checked before being trusted. This matters even more because graduate hiring is under pressure: the ISE says graduate recruitment fell 8% in the 2024/25 cycle, with a further 7% decline forecast for 2025/26, and particularly steep expected falls in Digital & IT (-53%). In a tighter market, screening becomes sharper.

How recruitment has changed

The most important number here is not a jobs number but a process number. The ISE's Student Recruitment Survey found that 33% of employers say generative AI is already leading them to redesign their selection processes, up from 23% the year before. A further 46% say they are reviewing their processes in response to generative AI, and 62% expect to use AI in recruitment going forward. That means AI is no longer a side issue in hiring. It is shaping the assessment environment itself.

The pattern is quite specific. Employers are not handing everything over to machines. ISE found that high-touch activities such as in-person interviews, group tasks, case studies and role play remain overwhelmingly human-led. But earlier and more structured stages are becoming more automated or hybrid. Numerical reasoning tests are 57% fully automated, situational judgement tests 53%, and verbal reasoning tests 49%. Hybrid human-system approaches are most common in strengths-based aptitude tests (42%), online job simulations (33%), and behavioural or values assessments (30%). In other words, candidates increasingly meet automated or semi-automated filters before they ever get to the most human parts of the process.

That shift is happening alongside a credibility problem. ISE reports that only 15% of employers in 2025 said they had never suspected or identified cheating in assessments, and the most commonly reported form of misconduct was candidates using AI during interviews without disclosure or permission, cited by 61% of respondents. So employers are not just adding AI to recruitment; they are redesigning recruitment partly to defend against shallow or misleading AI use by candidates.

What "AI literacy" actually means to a hiring manager

This is where many candidates get it wrong. AI literacy is not just prompt speed or tool familiarity. The strongest evidence on this comes from the direction employers are moving. ISE found that employers still prefer human judgement for nuanced evaluation, and 71% say they prefer a more human-centric recruitment process, while 67% worry about bias in AI decision-making. That implies that the candidates who look strongest are not the ones claiming AI can do everything faster; they are the ones who understand oversight, limits and verification.

That broader interpretation is echoed in current career-market analysis. A recent Collab365 briefing argues that basic conversational prompting is already commoditised, and that the real differentiator is the ability to set constraints, audit outputs for hallucinations, document human-in-the-loop iteration and produce usable business artefacts rather than generic text. That is not a replacement for employer survey data, but it fits the direction of travel. Hiring managers are increasingly looking for applied judgement, not AI hype.

So, in practical terms, AI literacy now means things like this: knowing how to use AI to accelerate work without skipping accountability; being able to explain how you verify outputs; understanding where sensitive data, compliance or fairness issues make AI use risky; and showing that you can combine AI with domain knowledge rather than outsource your thinking to it. Those are exactly the kinds of capabilities that become valuable when employers are redesigning assessments and protecting against misuse.

The red flags and green flags

A red flag in 2026 is not simply "uses AI." It is careless overstatement. If a candidate says, "I use AI for everything and it makes me 10x faster," a hiring manager can reasonably hear risk: poor judgement, weak verification habits, possible confidentiality problems, and someone who may not know when human review matters. That is an inference, but it is a grounded one given employer concern about bias, cheating and the continued reliance on human-led assessment in more subjective stages.

A green flag looks different. It sounds more like: "I use AI to speed up first drafts, research synthesis and workflow preparation, but I verify facts, sense-check outputs, and keep humans in the loop for decisions that affect quality, compliance or people." That signals operational maturity. It matches the labour market's shift toward candidates who can supervise AI well rather than simply operate it noisily. Even LinkedIn commentary on the rise of AI-led recruitment has noticed the irony: to get hired, candidates increasingly have to understand the systems reshaping work itself.

What education providers need to teach

This has a direct implication for colleges, universities and careers teams. Teaching "what AI is" is no longer enough. Students need practical AI literacy: how to use AI in research and writing without crossing integrity lines, how to document verification, how to talk about human oversight, and how to present proof of applied capability. In a market where graduate hiring is shrinking and employers are redesigning selection around AI, that is employability content, not optional enrichment.

The smartest providers will start teaching candidates how to demonstrate responsible AI use in CVs, applications, portfolios and interviews. That means moving beyond theory and into practice: evidence of workflow improvement, examples of checking and refinement, and language that shows discernment rather than dependence.`},
  {title:"The AI Skills Boost — Is Free Training Enough?",summary:"More than 1 million AI course completions is a strong start, but completion is not the same as workplace capability. Employers that want real value will need role-specific, structured AI upskilling rather than generic awareness alone.",category:"Business",read_time:"5 minutes",slug:"the-ai-skills-boost-is-free-training-enough",date:"2026-03-06",featured:false,body:`When a national programme passes 1,001,147 AI course completions, it is tempting to call it a breakthrough. And in one sense, it is. The government's AI Skills Boost has moved quickly, brought together major industry partners, and widened access to free AI learning across the UK. It is also tied to a big ambition: upskilling 10 million workers by 2030. That scale matters. But for employers, the more important question is not how many people completed a course. It is whether those people can now use AI in ways that improve performance, reduce friction and create measurable value at work.

The answer, at least so far, is: only partly. AI Skills Boost deserves credit for getting AI learning into the mainstream. But free, generic courses alone will not close the gap between curiosity and capability. For that, organisations need something more structured, more role-specific and more closely tied to real workflows.

What the AI Skills Boost actually offers

The programme itself is more serious than some critics assume. AI Skills Boost is a joint government-industry initiative designed to improve workforce readiness by upskilling 10 million UK workers by 2030. It was announced as part of a broader push to expand free AI training nationwide, with support from large employers and technology companies. The wider January 2026 package also included £27 million in funding aimed at connecting people to tech jobs in local communities and supporting new professional practice courses and graduate traineeships.

Skills England's contribution is especially useful because it introduces a clearer baseline. Its AI foundation skills for work benchmark focuses on four practical areas: understanding AI risks and consequences, creating prompts and adapting settings, using simple AI dashboards to interpret trends, and automating routine tasks with AI tools. Learners who complete benchmark-aligned courses receive a digital badge that can be used on CVs and online profiles. That gives the programme a bit more structure than a random collection of short courses.

That matters because many employers, especially SMEs, still struggle to define what "AI skills" actually means for their teams. Skills England's own research says poor employer understanding is part of the problem, and its benchmark is intended to create a more common language. That is a meaningful step forward.

The gap between completion and capability

Still, there is a gap between course completion and workplace capability. A short online course can help someone understand prompting, basic risk awareness or simple automation. It does not automatically teach a sales manager how to redesign customer research with AI, an operations lead how to build human-checking protocols into reporting, or an HR team how to use AI safely in recruitment and policy drafting. Those are role-specific capabilities, and they usually need guided practice, use-case design and some form of internal governance.

This is where criticism of the programme has some force. People Management argued that the current offer mainly broadens access to short introductory courses and that much of the guidance already risks becoming outdated because the technology is moving so quickly. That does not make the programme a failure. It does mean employers should avoid treating course completions as proof that the organisation is now AI-ready.

The economic case for going further is strong. Government's explainer cites IMF evidence showing that AI skills in the UK are associated with a 7.5-8% wage premium within occupations. It also says that if the programme reaches 10 million workers and unlocked even a cautious 1% output gain, that could equate to more than £7.5 billion in additional GVA per year. But government is clear that this estimate is uncertain. The upside is real; the route to capturing it is what matters.

And employers are still feeling the broader skills pressure. ManpowerGroup's 2026 research found that 73% of UK employers report talent shortages, only slightly down from 76% the year before. It also found that AI-related capability is now the hardest skill area to find, not in the narrow sense of specialist developers, but in everyday literacy and confidence using AI well in existing roles.

What employers actually need

What most organisations need now is not just access to AI learning. They need structured AI upskilling. That means training designed around functions and decisions, not just around tools. A finance team needs different AI habits from a marketing team. A college leadership team needs different safeguards from a logistics operation. The learning pathway should reflect the job, the risk level and the business process being improved.

They also need evaluation. The useful question is not, "Who completed a course?" It is, "What can this team now do better, faster or more safely than before?" Without that link to outcomes, AI learning becomes a participation metric rather than a productivity strategy.

Making it work for your organisation

The practical route is straightforward. First, assess current AI maturity. Work out where AI is already being used, where it is banned in practice, and where people are improvising with no common rules. That gives you the real baseline.

Second, identify role-specific needs. Start with the functions where AI could remove repetitive work, improve decision quality or strengthen output consistency. Then define the exact behaviours needed for each role, including verification and risk controls.

Third, build a learning pathway, not a one-off course list. Use free foundational training where it helps, but layer it with internal guidance, live use cases, manager support and simple measures of whether the learning is changing work. That is how broad awareness becomes capability.

AI Skills Boost is a welcome national start. It lowers the barrier, creates a shared foundation and puts AI learning in front of more people than ever before. But free training is only enough if your ambition is awareness. If your ambition is performance, employers need something deeper.`},
  {title:"The DfE\'s Quiet Revolution — AI Product Safety Standards Are Now Mandatory",summary:"In January 2026, the DfE quietly toughened its AI-in-education framework from \'product safety expectations\' to \'product safety standards\'. For colleges, that changes AI procurement from a loose innovation question into a much more formal governance and compliance issue.",category:"Education",read_time:"4 minutes",slug:"the-dfes-quiet-revolution-ai-product-safety-standards-are-now-mandatory",date:"2026-03-07",featured:false,body:`A lot of colleges are still treating AI procurement as if the rules are broadly the same as they were a year ago. They are not. In January 2026, the Department for Education updated its guidance from Generative AI: product safety expectations to Generative AI: product safety standards, and the change was more than editorial. The DfE now says these are the "minimum expected" safeguards AI products should meet to be considered safe in educational settings, and schools and colleges may use them to assess whether tools are suitable for use. That is not the same as a new Act of Parliament, but it is a clear shift from optional best-practice language toward a harder procurement benchmark.

The quiet part matters. The page itself was first published on 22 January 2025 and updated on 19 January 2026. The official update note says the 2026 revision added new standards on cognitive development, emotional and social development, mental health, and manipulation. That is a major widening of scope. The DfE is no longer focused only on filtering, data protection and general safety. It is now explicitly setting expectations about how AI tools affect how learners think, feel, engage and develop.

What changed between 2025 and 2026

The 2025 version was framed as expectations. Archived copies of that original guidance use exactly that term and describe the framework as outlining capabilities and features products "should meet" to be considered safe. By 2026, the live GOV.UK page had been retitled product safety standards, and the DfE had inserted new sections that describe the safeguards as the minimum expected measures for learner-facing products. Darren Coxon's analysis captured the practical implication well: this is a move from aspirational guidance toward requirements that will shape product roadmaps and procurement decisions.

That matters because colleges are already being told to use these materials in decision-making. The DfE's broader AI in education guidance says colleges should make safety their top priority, consider safeguarding and data protection, and refer to the product safety framework when deciding on AI use. It also says pupils should only use generative AI with appropriate safeguards in place. In other words, the standards are now part of the normal due-diligence environment for educational AI, not an optional side document.

The four new requirements

The most striking addition is cognitive development. The DfE says learner-facing products should use progressive disclosure, prompt learners for input first, and only show a full solution after a genuine learner attempt. It also expects products to detect and report forms of cognitive offloading, such as revealing a full solution, pasting in generated text, or using a "generate the full answer" option. That is a big signal: the department is actively trying to stop AI from replacing the learning process itself.

Then there is emotional and social development. The standards say products should not anthropomorphise themselves or imply emotions, personhood, agency or identity. They should avoid "I think" phrasing outside tightly bounded pedagogical roleplay, avoid avatars or naming conventions that suggest personhood, and avoid language that could isolate a learner from real-world support. Products should also include default time limits, enforce hard usage limits that only a teacher or administrator can reset, and alert the DSL where patterns suggest emotional dependence or safeguarding concern.

The other two new sections are mental health and manipulation. On mental health, the DfE says products should detect signs of distress, route learners toward human help, avoid validating harmful thought patterns, and maintain a crisis protocol. On manipulation, the standards prohibit tactics such as flattery, pressure to conform, fear-based nudges, misleading confidence, dark patterns and exploitative engagement design. This is far more detailed than most college procurement checklists currently are.

What this means for your procurement process

The practical takeaway is simple: colleges should now assume that any serious AI procurement process needs a DfE standards check. A vendor saying "we are safe for education" is no longer enough. Procurement leads should be asking whether the tool supports progressive disclosure, whether it logs cognitive offloading, whether it uses anthropomorphic language, what usage limits exist, what safeguarding alerts are built in, and how mental-health escalation is handled. Those are no longer niche technical questions. They are core suitability questions.

The sector is already responding. Heather Backstrom noted that the January 2026 FEA-I model policy was updated to reflect the latest DfE, Ofsted and Ofqual guidance, with stronger expectations around safeguarding, procurement, high-stakes decision making and assessment integrity. FE News has added the wider strategic frame: if colleges want to stay ahead, three priorities now matter most — strong governance, meaningful AI literacy and purposeful engagement with EdTech Testbeds.

Practical steps for this term

This term, colleges should do three things. First, audit current AI tools against the new DfE standards, especially any learner-facing products. Second, update procurement and AI policy language so staff and governors are working from the 2026 standards rather than older expectations-based wording. Third, consider how the government's expanding EdTech Testbeds programme fits into your evidence strategy: the DfE has committed £23 million to expand the pilot, with schools and colleges testing tools that reduce workload, improve outcomes and support inclusion.

This is a quiet update, but it changes the ground beneath AI procurement. Colleges that keep buying tools as if the old guidance still applies will drift into risk. Colleges that treat the new DfE standards as a procurement baseline will be in a much stronger position on safeguarding, governance and inspection readiness.`},
];

